ctivism and Education of people living with HIV and Aids and the population in general in order to motivate, orientate and develop prevention activities. \r\n\r\nVision: To be a reference to governmental and nongovernmental institutions, nationally and internationally that works in the area of STI/Aids and Human Rights, and to society as a whole, through promoting ethical debates, commitment, political activism and efficiency in the prevention and assistance/ support activities that the organisation develops. \r\n\r\n\r\nBeneficiary groups: People living with HIV and Aids, male sex professionals (young men and transvestites), women, young people and old people in a situation of social and economic risk.             \r\n\r\nPrevious TIE experience: Wieden + Kennedyâ€™s CP Ryan Fisher participated on a TIE placement in November, 2008. Partnering with ad agency INATA, he helped to develop a communications campaign to promote the Solidarity Kitchen, one of GTP+â€™s projects that empowers people living with HIV, provide good quality food for a fair price and also helps to sustain the NGOâ€™s activities. The effort was a great success, doubling Kitchen sales in the first six months and increasing its income by about 300% after the first year. \r\n\r\nNow hosting a TIE placement for the second time, GTP+ intends to fight discrimination and prejudice against people with HIV/Aids.  \r\n',NULL,21,9,NULL),(452,218,2,'Main point of contact within organisation','*Wladimir Reis*: General coordinator. Wladmir is one of the founders of GTP+, and he has been living with HIV since 1994. At the end of the 1990s AIDS began to reach people from the communities of Recife that were economically and socially vulnerable. The organisation began to organise itself during this time, due partly to the fact that during this time the first lots of Aids medication began to arrive n Brazil (AZT). Wladimir was fundamental in promoting this agenda in Recife. ',NULL,21,10,NULL),(453,219,2,'Other points of contact','*Emma Arnold*: Emma is a development worker from the NGO International Service. International Service is a development organization that places international development professionals with small NGOs during two year periods. Emma has been working with GTP+ since October 2007 in the area of institutional strengthening. She will be on of the main point sof contact for proving English translation during the placement. The other main points of contact do not speak English. She will have a good knowledge of GTP+ as an organization. \r\n\r\n*Emanuela Castro*: Emanuela is the head of communications for GTP+. She doesnâ€™t speak English, but she has been with the organization for a while and is the main point of contact for all things communications related. You will work quite closely with her throughout the development of the campaign.  ',NULL,21,11,NULL),(454,220,2,'Other partners in the project','The advertising agency INATA, which is linked to the Barros Melo/AESO University in Olinda is the local advertising agency involved in this project. You will work in partnership with INATA during your time in Recife. This partnership is crucial for the success of this placement for a number of reasons. First of all, the local professionals will provide the local language and cultural knowledge necessary for the placementâ€™s success. Also, you will have the opportunity to share skills and experiences, providing you with the international experience and skill exchange necessary for growth and professional development. Third, this will provide a common ground for you while learning about the industry of development, which is very different from the world of communications, and possibly slightly overwhelming. You will have the opportunity to learn how to approach this new area together, drawing on past communication experiences to discover the best solutions for the placement. \r\nINATA is a university that specializes in advertising/publicity; as such you will have the opportunity to work with advertising professors and students, although one individual will be chosen as the focal point or the project. INATA has already worked with GTP+ and they will be able to provide important information about current and previous communications strategies of GTP+. \r\n\r\nINATA has been working closely with TIE in a number of previous placements, including the one weâ€™ve cited before, when Ryan Fisher helped to develop a communications campaign to promote GTP+â€™s Solidarity Kitchen. \r\n\r\nYou will be responsible for managing these relationships and ensuring that all parties are aware of what is happening at all times when creating the communications materials. ',NULL,21,28,NULL),(455,221,2,'Background and overview of main objectives','There are many ways that people with HIV and AIDS face discrimination throughout their day-to-day lives. \r\n\r\nRegarding the family, there are many examples where families reject their HIV+ family members, not only because they are living with HIV, but also because of the connotations that the virus carries; homosexuality, drug use and prostitution, for example.  \r\n\r\nIn the beginning of the AIDS epidemic in the 1980s the profile of people living with HIV was mostly the big opinion makers in society (heads of industry, commerce, etc.). However, they didnâ€™t talk about their illness. And neither did their families.  When asked where the person was, they were often told to be studying in Europe or the U.S.. But in reality they were often isolated in a room of the house, or in hospital, with a health problem.  \r\n\r\nGTP+ often see HIV-positive people who are virtually disowned by their family.  There are many examples of people who are tested positive, forced to move out of the house, and spend the last years of their life buying food, going to the doctor and going to GTP+. GTP+ have often accompanied people in the last years of their life who have not once had visits from their family members, and essentially died alone. \r\nThen there is the media. Often, peopleâ€™s serology (when positive) is headlined when the media relates to sexual crimes committed by people living with HIV/AIDS. However, this increases stigma against this population, leading society to assume that people living with the virus are particularly â€˜dangerousâ€™.  \r\nIn October 2009, there were articles published in the 2 main newspapers in Recife that had splashed across the headlines that a sexual assault was committed by a 24 year old with a disabled person. The texts read \"HIV-positive man rapes disabled boy\" and \"Young abused by HIV-positive\". The problem here is that the media is criminalizing the person for living with HIV, not for the crime that he committed. Of course what he did was wrong, but it has nothing to do with the fact that he has HIV that it was wrong.  \r\n\r\nHIV is not the crime. Raping someone is. \r\n\r\nThe problem is that the cruelty associated with HIV does not reflect the behavior of most people living with the virus. In this case, the person who committed the violence should be judged for the act of violence itself, regardless of his HIV status. And it is these sorts of headlines that are creating more stigma and discrimination for this population.  \r\nThere are also many cases of people with HIV/AIDS who suffer discrimination in the workplace, which can take many forms, including: the obligation to make HIV testing in recruitment and the consequent refusal of employment, dismissal on the grounds of HIV status, actual or supposedly, the exclusion of training and promotion opportunities, prejudice on the part of co-workers, and the exclusion of the benefits of health insurance, among others.  \r\nAs well, when people are made redundant for having the virus, they are often not paid their redundancy payment because it is believed that they will die quickly.  Luckily there are many cases of people who go to court and win their labour rights, but it just goes to show how the system currently works here.  \r\n\r\nThere are many stories that GTP+ can share around this area of work discrimination. In fact, many of the people working at GTP+ are there because they were kicked out of their previous employment because of their HIV status.  \r\nHowever, unrelated to people at GTP+, there was the case of an elderly HIV-positive man who worked as a health worker. After six months he was dismissed from the secretary of health, citing grounds of dereliction of duty.  The truth was that he was asked to leave after he revealed his HIV status to managers.  \r\n\r\nThere are obviously many more stories than these above, but hopefully they help paint the very real picture here in Brazil, and help you understand the background to the project objective.  The new campaign intends to contradict these biased assumptions, fighting discrimination against the people living with the virus. ',NULL,21,13,NULL),(456,222,2,'Social development objective','To decrease discrimination amongst the population as a whole about people who are living with HIV and AIDS. \r\n',NULL,21,14,NULL),(457,223,2,'Overall objective','Fight the stigma of delinquency about people living with HIV/Aids ',NULL,21,12,NULL),(458,224,2,'Where will I be located?','* You will be located in the city of Recife, in the North Eastern state of Pernambuco, Brazil. \r\n\r\n* Your time will be divided between the offices of GTP+ and the advertising Agency INATA. INATA is in Olinda and is 20 minutes by bus from GTP+. You will decide jointly with INATA and GTP+ how much time you should spend at each place.  Keep in mind that INATA is only open in the afternoons and their availability is based around the times that they have classes. \r\n',NULL,21,15,NULL),(459,225,2,'Further information on the family','You will be staying with a family when youâ€™re in Brazil. The family lives in a community called BrasÃ­lia Teimosa and itâ€™s right by the beach. Everyone in the area knows each other and itâ€™s always busy â€“ perfect for safety. I have spoken to many development workers who have stayed there and they all felt perfectly safe. Most people that stay there are German or British â€“ so many fairheads and lots of girls. Itâ€™s a great intro to Brazil.\r\n\r\nYou will have your own room, which has a desk, a fan and a cupboard for your clothes. The place is really clean, friendly, and there is even a dog to keep you company! The family donâ€™t speak English, but this will really help you with your Portuguese and help you settle into your life in Brazil. Probably a good idea to get one of those phrase books so that you can figure out how to talk about certain things when youâ€™re there. There is breakfast and dinner for you and that is included in the overall cost for TIE â€“ so you donâ€™t have to worry about that when youâ€™re eating at home. One thing to keep in mind, however, is that the big meal of the day is had at lunch-time, and this will obviously be when youâ€™re working. So when eating at home expect bread, cheese, fruit, eggs, meat, couscous etc.\r\n\r\nThere is a laundry facility and you can use this once a week if you bring your own soap etc. There may also be a cost for this. There is also Internet in the house, but as its pretty slow they suggest you go to the local internet cafÃ© which is cheap, a much faster connection, and provides you with an opportunity to meet more people in the community.\r\n\r\nThey are based right by the bus station too, or short walk for more buses that come from Boa Viagem. The family are lovely and will help you find your way around.\r\n\r\nJust ask them to help you out and theyâ€™ll make sure youâ€™re going in the right direction. Your map will really come in handy, so try to keep a hold of it.\r\n\r\nTIE only covers your accommodation for 1 month. If you decide to stay on longer, that is fine, but please communicate these details with the family in order to organise this, and please make sure that you pay them for any extra days that you stay. ',NULL,21,16,NULL),(460,226,2,'Further expectations','You will be expected to take part in the TIE UK and in-country training. Before the day of your UK training you will receive an email pack of reading material to help you prepare. We suggest that you read as much as possible before taking part as youâ€™ll benefit just so much more that way!  ',NULL,21,17,NULL),(461,227,2,'Personal reflection log','It is recommended that throughout the placement you fill out a personal reflection log. This will aid in your personal and professional learning journey. We would recommend that you try and separate the diary into personal and professional experiences. This is actually quite key, as you will use this when filling out your evaluations and analyzing your experience at the end of the placement, when writing your case study, and putting together your presentation. Doing it this way will really help make sense of everything along the way â€“ from both perspectives. Please note that this will be a confidential document â€“ unless you choose to make it public through a blog, or diary that can be uploaded onto the website. \r\n ',NULL,21,18,NULL),(462,228,2,'Evaluation, case study, presentations and follow up','We do require an evaluation to be filled out at the end of your assignment. This will include your outline of ideas for other related assignments in the organisation, conclusions regarding your personal and business objectives, thoughts on the experience, your learnings and an assessment of placement and the social impact. â€“ see later sections. A presentation and case study on the experience will also need to be put together. When you are back home your agency, client, the IPA or other industry institutions may want to hear about your experience. This is a great opportunity to communicate your experience, the situation in Brazil, and help people understand what your organisation focuses on and stands for. As well, your case study will be put on the website so that other people are able to learn about the work you did, about the NGO in Brazil, and the issues facing developing countries.\r\n\r\nFinally, we are organising Friends of TIE events that will take place about once a year. These are an opportunity for people to share their experiences, pictures, learnings and stories, meet like-minded people, and help us understand how we can improve things moving forward. You may be asked to present at one of these events. ',NULL,21,19,NULL),(463,229,2,'When will the project start and how long will it last?','It will run for a month and start in 2010 ',NULL,21,20,NULL),(464,230,2,'What skills and experiences are required for the placement?','This is a high level assignment that requires a good grasp of the organisation and communications. The CP will be required to work with many different stakeholders within the organisation, and different players on the placement. It will be the responsibility of the UK CP to manage all of the relationships and make sure that everyone is aware of what is happening at all times. The assignment will require good communication skills, empathy, listening skills, flexibility, team working skills, communication planning skills, creativity, project management skills and an ability to look at the big picture. It is vital that the CP is open to learning from other people during this placement.\r\n\r\nIt would also be good if the CP has an interest in promoting the rights of people living with HIV and AIDS.\r\n\r\nThe communications professional team will be made up of an account person/planner and a creative. If the UK CP is an account person/planner, then the local CP will need to be a creative and vice versa.\r\n\r\nThe placement will be held in a non-English speaking country. Although GTP+ has English-speaking people, and the local CP will speak English, it is advisable that the UK CP speaks another language, preferably Spanish or Portuguese. Finally, no prejudices or negative attitudes will be acceptable. ',NULL,21,21,NULL),(465,231,2,'What can the professional do within the organization to make this assignment a success?','* Integrate with the members of GTP+ and the other partners involved in the process. These are the actors that will put into practice the actions that will be planned and developed by you;\r\n* Get to grips with the activities of GTP+;\r\n* Work jointly with the user groups of GTP+, using an approach that promotes their rights and does not view them as passive recipients of charity, and that places them at the centre of the process of elaboration of communications materials. The idea being that any activity that will affect them or that talks about them, should include them â€“ â€˜Nothing about us without usâ€™;\r\n* Work together with the students of INATA and involve them throughout the process;\r\n* Develop an understanding and empathy with the organizational culture of GTP+ and the relationship that GTP+ has with the public;\r\n* Develop good communications with and between all members of the organization and the local communications agency. Keep everyone informed of what is happening and the developments at all times;\r\n* Understand who the target market is for each type of communications material created. E.g. what makes them tick, what are they into? Where will the communication material be placed? Are you targeting the youth/NGO/Community as a whole? What is the best media to reach these people?\r\n* Agree a process for implementing the use of the communication pieces and then work through the process with GTP+;\r\n* Ensure that all parties are in agreement with the objectives and any changes made during the placement;\r\n* Fully transfer capability, understanding and ownership to GTP+ staff before the end of the assignment so that the implementation is assured (this should be a gradual process of transfer during the assignment)',NULL,21,22,NULL),(466,232,2,'Who will benefit?','* People living with HIV and AIDS, groups of people in a vulnerable social situation and other groups that benefit from GTP+ services;\r\n* GTP+, through communication materials to help support and raise awareness of the organization;\r\n* The public in general that are reached by the communications materials, who will better understand the work of GTP+ and respect the rights of people living with HIV and AIDS;\r\n* The UK and the local communications professionals (INATA) will also benefit from the experience. They will have exposure to bigger picture communications problems, experience in-depth hands-on experience of business practice and build confidence to take on new roles and responsibilities.\r\n',NULL,21,23,NULL),(467,233,2,'Sustainability','According to a recent analysis of the importance of communication to NGOs as a tool to increase their effectiveness and sustainability, communication is seen to be ever more important. Not just for sustainability, but also for the fact that their main objective, to challenge current beliefs and reality about how the world functions, can only be properly achieved through effective communication. The problem - communications is currently seen to be a luxury by many NGOs. There is a strong and ever increasing demand for support in the area of communications within the NGO sector, and currently there is a significant deficit in terms of the support available. ',NULL,21,27,NULL),(468,234,2,'Communications is an increasingly important component of the work of NGOs and is crucial for...','* Capturing resources and increasing visibility;\r\n* Elaborating behavioral change messages;\r\n* Stimulating and promoting the voices of marginalized groups;\r\n* Engaging stakeholders and ensuring that projects and programs are planned, implemented and monitored with the active participation of stakeholders;\r\n* Lobbying policy makers, networking and raising awareness of social development issues locally, nationally and globally;\r\n* Increasing internal organizational capacity and professionalizing the NGO sector;\r\n* Increasing visibility, engaging stakeholders and raising awareness of social development issues locally, nationally and globally;\r\n* Increased sustainability and impact of NGOs.\r\n* TIE provides communications support in a specific time-bound way whilst creating opportunities for longer-term support through partners and, in the long term, through participatory and effective knowledge management.\r\n* Through the placements TIE will therefore help raise awareness of the importance of communications, transfer knowledge to members of the local partner organizations, create a strong link between the private and development sectors, and help strengthen the voice of the organizations.\r\n\r\nTIE provides communications support in a specific time-bound way whilst creating opportunities for longer-term support through partners and, in the long term, through participatory and effective knowledge management.\r\n\r\nThrough the placements TIE will therefore help raise awareness of the importance of communications, transfer knowledge to members of the local partner organizations, create a strong link between the private and development sectors, and help strengthen the voice of the organizations. ',NULL,21,26,NULL),(469,235,2,'PERSONAL OBJECTIVES','...',NULL,21,29,NULL),(470,236,2,'What personal development does the assignment offer?','In addition to the creation of the specific personal development objectives that this process facilitates and that are described in the next section, this assignment also provides the opportunity to:\r\n\r\n* Work under pressure in a totally different organisation, country and culture without the normal corporate support systems and services\r\n* Gain an understanding of the structure, operation, culture, politics and requirements of a complex business in a very short time\r\n* Understand the development sector and understand how to connect the private sector with the not-for-profit sector in a more effective way\r\n* Exposure to bigger picture communications problems and test out your overall communications skills in a new context\r\n* Build confidence to take on new roles and responsibilities\r\n* Challenge your negotiating and influencing skills to ensure that the results of your assignment are fully embedded and stand a high chance of long-term sustainability\r\n* Build cross-cultural understanding and sensitivity\r\n* Challenge the communication professional to simultaneously balance the achievement short term results with the creation of a sustainable model for long-term growth\r\n* Stimulate creativity and out-of-the-box thinking',NULL,21,24,NULL),(471,237,2,'What are my specific personal objectives for this assignment?','The personal objectives relate to the UK CPâ€™s agreed development needs and any other personal aims (e.g. to make a positive social contribution). The candidate will add them with input from other sources such as their HR director, line manager, or TIEâ€™s Development Coach. The personal objectives must be finalised in advance of the assignment. It is important that during the placement the Personal Reflection Log is filled out, as this will help monitor this learning journey and help re-evaluate goals and objectives (both personal and professional) along the way. ',NULL,21,25,NULL),(472,238,2,'What are your motivations/expectations?','To be filled in by the CP ',NULL,21,30,NULL),(473,239,2,'Stakeholders','You can use this section to note down who the important stakeholders are for the personal objectives for the assignment and engage them when appropriate. To be filled in by the CP. \r\n',NULL,21,34,NULL),(474,240,2,'BUSINESS OBJECTIVES','...',NULL,21,32,NULL),(475,241,2,'What are the business objectives for this placement?','These objectives relate to what the agency will achieve through the placement. They are likely to relate to the development needs of the candidate, in which case the objectives should be framed in the Agencyâ€™s terms. There may also be business objectives relating to knowledge / intellectual capital, Corporate Responsibility, better understanding of the global economy and emerging markets, demonstration of corporate values and other strategic initiatives, and these should also be recorded in this section. The business objectives summarise the business case for the placement and it is the candidateâ€™s responsibility to research, define and agree these objectives in advance of the assignment with HR or their line manager. ',NULL,21,33,NULL),(476,242,2,'Stakeholders','You can use this section to note down who the important stakeholders are for the business objectives for the assignment and engage them when appropriate. ',NULL,21,31,NULL),(477,243,2,'SOCIAL OBJECTIVES','...',NULL,21,35,NULL),(478,244,2,'What social outcomes are expected from this assignment?','Outcomes are the organisational changes that should come about as a result of the placement. Outcomes might be observed immediately or soon after the assignment or may not be evident for some period of time. For the local organisations, social impact outcomes will be of particular importance and the candidate has the responsibility of agreeing the short and longer-term outcomes with the stakeholders of the organisation',NULL,21,36,NULL),(479,245,2,'How can I assess impact outcomes from my assignment?','To gain insights into the impact of the assignment, the candidate is encouraged to involve the organisation and other stakeholders, as appropriate, in a discussion to assess the social impact from the assignment. Some of the impact may be immediate while other impacts are likely to happen over a longer time frame. The candidate should aim to document all the impacts (both positive and negative) as far as possible. More of this will be covered off in the evaluation at the end of the placement, but its important to start thinking about what will be considered in this section. ',NULL,21,37,NULL),(480,246,2,'FURTHER INFORMATION','...',NULL,21,38,NULL),(481,247,2,'Placement logistics','* You will be based part time at the local agency and part time at GTP+ office downtown Recife. At both places you will have a desk to work at;\r\n* You will work a 5-day week, and will work the hours necessary to get the job done. Use the local CP and GRP work hours as a base to work from. If more time is needed to get the job done, you will be expected to work overtime. It is important that you treat this placement like you would treat your work back at home;\r\n* You will be responsible for taking a laptop computer;\r\n* Interpreters are not needed. But, again, Portuguese or Spanish knowledge are certain a plus if you want to communicate better with more people;\r\n* You will be staying with a local family in Recife. They will provide you with a room and meals; and\r\n* You will have someone from TIE pick you up from the airport',NULL,21,39,NULL),(482,248,2,'Fundraising','You will be expected to fundraise a minimum of Â£1000 for your placement. This money will then go to the organisation for the communications materials that you produce when there. You, the local CP and GTP+ will all discuss how best to spend the money. ',NULL,21,40,NULL),(483,249,2,'Costs','The cost of the placement includes: Programme management fee, accommodation, food when at the accommodation, UK & in country training, airport pick up, orientation/transportation/information on the city, local contact person in case of emergency, Brazilian SIM card and first batch of minutes, pre-departure information and support, and a fundraising pack to help with the fundraising.\r\n\r\nYour agency is expected to cover the cost of the flight, insurance and visa (if needed). It is important that the you declare at airport that you are travelling for tourism and that your computer will be for personal records of the trip. You will be expected to pay for food (other than the meals included in your accommodation), entertainment costs, and any transport costs such as taxis or local buses. ',NULL,21,41,NULL),(484,250,2,'Risks','Safety is a risk in Brazil and anyone traveling to Brazil or living in the cities needs to be aware of this. Never flash cash, donâ€™t walk around with expensive objects such as cameras, watches or jewelry, and try and keep as little money on you at any one time. Also, donâ€™t walk down the street talking on your mobile, and try not to carry big handbags. If something is to happen, and someone is to mug you, it is extremely important to hand over whatever it is that they want. Fighting with the people, or avoiding giving them what they want is not advisable and may lead to more harm than good. It is a beautiful country and the people are amazing, but like any developing country, there is crime, and you need to be aware of how to avoid it and what to do should something happen. Look around and see what the locals are doing â€“ and do your best to blend in. As well, it is important to note that Brazil is an AIDS high-risk country. Therefore, please take the appropriate precautions. ',NULL,21,42,NULL),(485,251,2,'Opportunities','This placement will open your mind. You will be immersed 100% in a new culture and be expected to run a project from beginning to end. You will learn how to work in a new environment, be exposed to bigger picture communications problems, build confidence to take on new roles and responsibilities, build cross-cultural understanding and sensitivity, learn to deal effectively with ambiguity, develop self awareness, improve interpersonal and influencing styles, experience in-depth hands- on experience of business practice and development issues in emerging markets, develop an improved understanding of the third sector and make an unforgettable contribution to development. ',NULL,21,43,NULL),(486,252,2,'T.I.E. CONTACT DETAILS','',NULL,21,44,NULL),(487,252,3,'T.I.E. CONTACT DETAILS','|Objective|Activities|Actorsenvolved|Outcomes|\r\n|Fight stigma of delinquency abo